Part A - Intro & Learning Activities¶

Notes From Slides¶

Reduced Chi-squared¶

  1. Start with the residuals
  2. Normalize residuals using uncertainty
  3. Square the normalized residuals and add them together. We square them so that both positive and negative residuals all add up
  4. Divide by the number of data points, N so that a set with more points isn't penalized/ We also want a model with more parameters to be penalized. P is the number of parameters in the model - for a straight line with only an adjustable slope, P=1. If a non-zero intercept is allowed, P=2.

Interpreting Reduced Chi-squared Value¶

  • If = 1: The models fit the data well, assuming uncertainties have been characterized well
  • If >> 1: Not a good fit or the uncertainties have been underestimated
  • If << 1: The uncertainties have been overestimated
  • Side Note: When using chi-squared, the goal is to adjust your fitting parameters in order to minimize the value for chi-squared, which indicates the best possible fit of your model to the data.
  • Side Note #2: The goal is not to make chi-squared = 1, it is to minimize it to find the best possible fit, and then interpret the resulting chi-squared value.

A Good Fit After Minimization¶

  • two-thirds of measurements within 1 deviation of the residuals zero-line
  • Almost all (95%) within 2 deviations of the residuals zero line
  • No trend in the data (data seems randomly scattered about the residuals zero line)

Experimental Goal¶

A comparison of the extent to which resistors and light bulbs obey Ohm's Law to determine the best fit slops to I vs V for a resistor and light bulb. In other words, we compare the degree to which these devices obey Ohm's Law.

Notes from video¶

In this lab, we will use Chi-squared to determine the best-fitting procedure. In last week's lab, we were given the residuals, and we used the residuals as the parameters in our model to determine when we reached the best fit. However, the limitation of that method is that it still requires more interpretation. Using chi-squared we can determine how good our model fit is. We will keep repeating this until we reach the minimized chi-squared (the best fit to the data).

Tips¶

  • Keep track of chi-squared value in a separate table to compare the different models' fits with different slopes
  • Try to minimize chi-squared value as close to 1 as possible for the best fit
  • Once you find the maximum and minimum best fit for slope value. Find the difference between the slope values and divide by 4 to get the uncertainty. Eg. if Max = 2.2 and Min = 2, uncertainty would be (2.2-2)/4=0.2/4=0.05 uncertainty

# Scatter Plot
# 1: find the limits of the data:
xmin = np.min(VVec) 
xmax = np.max(VVec)

# 2: generate a bunch of x points between xmin and xmax
xpoints = np.linspace(xmin, xmax, 100) 

# 3: calculate the model values:
slope = 0.0769 # Our initial estimate of the slope
ypoints = xpoints * slope 

# 4: plot the curve. We plot this as a red line "r-" :
plt.plot(xpoints, ypoints, "r-", label = "V = IR")

# 5: plot the data:
plt.errorbar(VVec, IVec, uIVec, fmt="bo", markersize = 3, label="Experimental data")
plt.title("Current vs. Voltage")
plt.xlabel("Voltage (V)")
plt.ylabel("Current (amp)")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Residuals plot
# Residuals step 1: Calculate the model at each x-datapoint
ymodel = slope * VVec # y = mx at each x_i

# Residuals step 2: Calcualte the residual vector
RVec = IVec - ymodel

# Calculate chi-squared
chi2 = np.sum((RVec/uIVec)**2)/(len(RVec)-1)
print("Weighted chi-squared: ", chi2)

# Resoduals step 3: Plot the residual vector against the x-data vector
plt.errorbar(VVec, RVec, uIVec, fmt="bo", markersize = 3)

# Residuals step 4: Add a R = 0 x-axis (horizontal line) to the plot
plt.hlines(y=0, xmin=xmin, xmax=xmax, color='k') # draw axis at y = 0.

# Residuals step 5: Add axis labels and title, and show the graph
plt.title("Residuals for Current vs. Voltage")
plt.xlabel("Voltage (V)")
plt.ylabel("Residual = data - model (N)")
plt.show()

Weighted chi-squared:  1.008730674088043

# slope and u[slope]
slope_max = 0.021
slope_min = 0.017
slope_best = 0.019
u_slope = (slope_max-slope_min)/2
print("The model slope is with 68% confidence interval: {:.4f}+/-{:.4f} N/m".format(slope_best, u_slope)) 
# u[slope]/slope
uSlopebySlope = u_slope/slope_best
# R and u_R
R = 1/slope_best
u_R = R* (u_slope/slope)
# u[R]/R
uRbyR = u_R/R 
print( "The calculated resistance of the resistor is: ", R)
print( "The calculated uncertainty of the resistor is: ", u_R)

Summarizing Comparisons With Other Groups¶

Tushar Dhillon got a slope of 0.0395 +/-0.00005 N/m with 68 % confidence interval. He got a resistance value of 27.1 Ω with an uncertainty of 0.073 Ω. Addressing the experimental goal and describing the conclusions from the results of your comparisons between the labs.¶

Ohm's Law states that the current through a device is proportional to the voltage applied to it $V = IR$. The experimental goal of this lab was to determine the best fit slopes to I vs V for a resistor and light bulb. In other words, we compare the degree to which these devices obey Ohm's Law. Using the collected data and the results stated above, I determined the resistance of the resistor and the bulb to be 52.63 Ω. This value is incorrect as at the beginning of the lab, we set the resistor value to 13.00 Ω. Therefore, based on the data above, the use of a light bulb in the circuit results in the bulb and resistor not obeying Ohm's Law. However, in the previous lab, we concluded that resistors alone do follow/obey Ohm's Law. Using the collected data and the results from lab 5, I determined the resistance of the resistor was 13.00 Ω (the same value as the expected resistance of 13.00 Ω).

  • Main point: Resistors follow Ohm's Law. Light bulbs do not follow Ohm's Law.
